	<h2>Our Mission</h2>
	<p>
		<strong>ErrorLedger</strong> is an independent, zero-trust technology incident database and deep-dive post-mortem research library[cite: 37]. We bypass generic media headlines to dissect the exact technical, physical, and software-driven root causes that trigger major global network failures[cite: 37].
	</p>
	<p>
		Our analyses translate real-world disaster scenarios into evergreen architectural lessons, helping systems engineers, software architects, and security operations teams build resilient, self-healing platforms[cite: 37].
	</p>

	<h2>The Sourcing Hierarchy</h2>
	<p>
		To prevent inaccuracy, speculation, and AI hallucinations, every incident record in our database is strictly compiled using a rigid primary-source authentication hierarchy:
	</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Tier 1 — Official Root Cause Analyses (RCAs):</strong> Post-mortem documentations, security advisories, and service health reports issued directly by the affected platforms.</li>
		<li><strong>Tier 2 — Threat Intel & Incident Forensics:</strong> Technical deconstructions from certified threat intelligence firms and verified engineering security blogs.</li>
		<li><strong>Tier 3 — Telemetry Logs:</strong> Public network route announcements, DNS records, and transaction ledger states.</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Why We Do Not Generate Code Fixes</h2>
	<p>
		Unlike typical programming blogs or package documentation engines, ErrorLedger does not publish quick patches, temporary API workarounds, or localized configuration hacks[cite: 37]. 
	</p>
	<p>
		Instead, we look at system-level behaviors—such as BGP routing cascades, out-of-bounds memory accesses in kernel space, or garbage collection deadlocks—to expose structural bugs and core trust boundary vulnerabilities[cite: 37]. We believe that truly understanding why a network collapsed is the most valuable step in preventing the next disaster.
	</p>
</Layout>